Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Trim the @aubergine{1} and halve lengthways. Chop each half into four long strips then chop widthways into roughly 3cm pieces. Chop the @cauliflower{1} into florets (little trees!). Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1/2%cup} in a #sieve{}.

Pop the cauliflower and aubergine on a lined #baking tray{}, drizzle with @oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Sprinkle on the @ground cumin{2%tsp} and half the @sumac{1%tsp}. Rub the flavourings all over the veggies and arrange in one layer. Roast on the top shelf of your oven until soft and nicely browned with burnt edges, ~{25-30%minutes}. Halfway through cooking, add the chickpeas to the tray and turn everything to make sure it browns evenly. Meanwhile, fill and boil your #kettle{}.

Halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and finely chopped) into small pieces. Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed then finely chop. Heat a drizzle of @oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Add the shallot and cook until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add a pinch of chilli and the @freekeh{100%g} and cook for ~{1%minute}. Stir in the boiling @water{200%ml} and @vegetable stock powder{1}. Bring to the boil then turn the heat to low, pop a #lid{} on and cook for ~{15%minutes}, then remove from the heat and leave to rest for ~{5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%bunch} (stalks and all). Pick the @mint{1%bunch} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Halve the @premium tomato mix{125%g}. Zest and juice the @lemon{1}. In a #bowl{}, combine the lemon zest, juice, herbs and tomatoes with the @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Season with a pinch of salt and pepper.

Take the @pistachios{25%g}(shelled and roughly chopped) out of their shells and roughly chop.

Fluff up the freekeh with a #fork{} and gently mix in half the salsa. Pop the freekeh pilaf into #bowls{} and top with the roasted veggies and chickpeas. Sprinkle over the pistachios, remaining sumac, any remaining chilli (if liked) and the other half of the salsa. Enjoy!

> Freekeh is a great source of dietary fibre, iron and zinc. It has a distinct nutty, smoky flavour.

> The tomato and herb salsa keeps the flavour fresh, whilst the addition of chickpeas, chopped pistachios and roasted veg make this a deliciously hearty and filling dish.